  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at preventing money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (UNTOC)\n\n2. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations, which provide international standards for combating money laundering\n\n3. The Palermo Convention, which addresses organized crime and money laundering\n\n4. The Basel Committee's guidelines on banking regulations\n\n5. The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) in the United States\n\n6. The European Union's Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n\nThese laws generally require financial institutions to:\n- Implement customer due diligence procedures\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Cooperate with international law enforcement\n\nMost countries have their own specific anti-money laundering (AML) laws that align with these international standards.",
